            <div type="edition">
                 <lg met="elegiacs">
                     <l><lb n="1"/>Τὸν λιγυρὸν κόλποις <persName><name key="Διονύσιος">Διονύσι
                     <lb n="2" break="no"/>ον</name></persName> ἐ<unclear>ν</unclear>θαδ’ ἔχ<unclear>ο</unclear><supplied reason= "lost">υ</supplied><unclear>σ</unclear>α</l> <l>γαῖα τὸν
                     <lb n="3"/>ἐν ζωοῖς ἤθεσι πραύτατον</l>
                     <lb n="4"/><l>δάκρυσον νεότητα καὶ εὐ
                     <lb n="5" break="no"/>στομίην <supplied reason= "lost">π</supplied><unclear>α</unclear><unclear>ρ</unclear>οδεῖτα,</l> <g type="hedera"/>
                     <lb n="6"/><l>μεμψάμενος Μοιρῶν
                     <lb n="7"/>τὴν ἄδικον <persName><name type="divine" key="Λάχεσις">Λά<supplied reason="lost">χ</supplied>εσιν</name></persName></l>. <g type="apex"/>
                     <lb n="8"/><g type="hedera"/>     
                  </lg>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
            <p> "Here in (her)
                    hollows the earth holds clear-voiced Dionysios, who in life was the gentlest in
                    character; shed a tear for (his) youth and eloquence, passerby, (and) blame the
                    unjust Lachesis of the Fates."</p></div>

            <div type="commentary">
            <p>Line 2: Haussoullier and Ingholt (1924: 337) noted that the participle (ἔχουσα)
                    rather than the expected indicative (ἔχει) is used here for metrical reasons,
                    but we should probably understand ἐστί, though a form of ἔχω make sense to me;
                    Peek also provides ἔχευσα or ἔχωσα as options. Line 7: there is either an apex
                    present as a punctuation mark at the end of the line or it is simply damage. The
                    lettering is uniform in style and consistent in height throughout, though the
                    last three lines have some space remaining.</p>
                <p> An epitaph for an eloquent youth, Dionysios—though the MFA refers to him mistakenly as Dionysion—praising his
                    virtue and lamenting his (early?) death in a pair of elegiac couplets (Τὸν
                    λιγυρὸν… πραύτατον, δάκρυσον… Λά[χ]εσιν). Dionysios is a common enough name
                    throughout antiquity (Solin noted 282 occurrences, making it the 15th most
                    common Greek name in his survey). The objects provenance makes an exact date
                    hard to ascertain, but the presence of the traditional Σ and Ω, rather than the
                    later lunate sigma (Ϲ) and double horseshoe omega (Ꞷ), suggest a date before the
                    fourth century C.E. </p></div>
            

